import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Count submissions per user_id
user_counts = task1responses['user_id'].value_counts()

# Define 10-submission-wide buckets up to 200
bins = list(range(0, 210, 10))  # [0, 10, 20, ..., 200]
labels = [f'{i+1}–{i+10}' for i in range(0, 200, 10)]  # ['1–10', '11–20', ..., '191–200']

# Bin the user counts
user_buckets = pd.cut(user_counts, bins=bins, labels=labels, right=True)

# Count how many users fall into each bucket
bucket_counts = user_buckets.value_counts().sort_index()

# Plot
plt.figure(figsize=(14, 6))
bucket_counts.plot(kind='bar')
plt.title('Number of Users by Submission Frequency Bucket (10-Submission Intervals)')
plt.xlabel('Number of Submissions')
plt.ylabel('Number of Users')
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

In [10]:
cols = [
        "Gender",
        "Education",
        "FinMarkEngagement",
        "AiEngagement",
        "RiskTolerance",
        "FamiliarityAI",
        "KnowledgeGenAI",
        "AITrust",
        "DecisionConfidence",
    ]

for col in cols:
        if col not in background_responses.columns:
            print(f"Column '{col}' not found in dataframe; skipping.")
            continue

        freq = (
            background_responses[col]
            .value_counts(dropna=False)
            .rename_axis(col)
            .reset_index(name="Count")
        )


        plt.figure()
        plt.bar(freq[col].astype(str), freq["Count"])
        plt.title(f"{col} (n={freq['Count'].sum()})")
        plt.xlabel(col)
        plt.ylabel("Count")
        plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha="right")
        plt.tight_layout()
        plt.show()

In [12]:
def extract_company_manipulation(image_name):
    image_name = str(image_name)  # convert to string to avoid AttributeError
    parts = image_name.split('.svg')
    company = parts[0]
    manipulation = parts[1].strip('_') if len(parts) > 1 else 'clean'
    return pd.Series([company, manipulation])

# Apply the function to create the new columns
df[['company', 'manipulation']] = df['image_name'].apply(extract_company_manipulation)


df['manipulation'] = df['manipulation'].replace(r'^\s*$', 'clean', regex=True)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Define plot bounds
max_val = 125
min_val = 75

# Loop through each unique user
for user in df['user_id'].unique():
    user_data = df[df['user_id'] == user]  # Only this user's data

    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))
    plt.scatter(user_data['true_midpoint'], user_data['user_estimate'],
                alpha=0.6, label='User Estimates')

    plt.plot([min_val, max_val], [min_val, max_val],
             color='red', linestyle='--', label='Perfect Estimation (y=x)')

    plt.xlabel('True Midpoint')
    plt.ylabel('User Estimate')
    plt.title(f'Estimates vs True Midpoints – User {user}')
    plt.legend()
    plt.grid(True)
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

In [20]:
stats = (
    df.groupby("manipulation")["answer_delta"]
      .agg(["mean", "count", "std"])
      .assign(se=lambda x: x["std"] / x["count"]**0.5)
      .reset_index()
)

# Plot: mean answer_delta with 1 SE error bars
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(6, 4))
ax.bar(stats["manipulation"], stats["mean"], yerr=stats["se"], capsize=5)
ax.set_xlabel("Manipulation")
ax.set_ylabel("Mean answer_delta (±1 SE)")
ax.set_title("Effect of manipulation on answer_delta")
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# Define thresholds
def categorize(value, tol=1e-6):
    if value > tol:
        return '> 0'
    elif value < -tol:
        return '< 0'
    else:
        return '≈ 0'

# Categorize mean differences
categorized = mean_diffs.applymap(categorize)

summary_table = categorized.apply(pd.Series.value_counts).fillna(0).astype(int)

# Optional: reorder rows
summary_table = summary_table.reindex(['> 0', '< 0'])

# Display the summary table
print(summary_table)

# 1. Filter clean and positive rows
clean_df = df[df["manipulation"] == "clean"].copy()
positive_df = df[df["manipulation"] == "positive"].copy()

# 2. Merge to get delta_from_clean per user and task (assuming 'task_id' exists)
delta_df = positive_df.merge(
    clean_df,
    on=["user_id", "company"],
    suffixes=("_pos", "_clean")
)
delta_df["delta_from_clean"] = delta_df["user_estimate_pos"] - delta_df["user_estimate_clean"]
In [27]:
# 2. Remove users with only one row (needed for random effects)
user_counts = delta_df["user_id"].value_counts()
valid_users = user_counts[user_counts > 1].index
delta_df = delta_df[delta_df["user_id"].isin(valid_users)]

# 3. Check variance (avoid singular matrix errors)
if delta_df["delta_from_clean"].var() < 1e-5:
    print("Not enough variance in delta_from_clean to fit model.")
else:
    try:
        # 4. Fit intercept-only mixed effects model
        model = smf.mixedlm("delta_from_clean ~ 1", delta_df, groups=delta_df["user_id"])
        mixed_result = model.fit(reml=False, method="lbfgs")
        print(mixed_result.summary())

        # 5. Extract random effects
        random_effects = mixed_result.random_effects
        random_df = pd.DataFrame.from_dict(random_effects, orient="index")
        random_df.columns = ["user_intercept"]
        random_df.index.name = "user_id"
        random_df = random_df.reset_index()
        print(random_df)

        # 6. Visualize random effects
        plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))
        plt.bar(random_df["user_id"].astype(str), random_df["user_intercept"])
        plt.axhline(0, color="gray", linestyle="--")
        plt.xlabel("User ID")
        plt.ylabel("Random Intercept")
        plt.title("User-Specific Random Intercepts (Positive Manipulation)")
        plt.xticks(rotation=45)
        plt.tight_layout()
        plt.show()

    except Exception as e:
        print("Model fitting failed:", e)

Negative vs. clean¶

import pandas as pd
import statsmodels.formula.api as smf

# 1. Filter clean and negative rows
clean_df = df[df["manipulation"] == "clean"].copy()
negative_df = df[df["manipulation"] == "negative"].copy()

# 2. Merge clean and negative responses per user and company
delta_df_neg = negative_df.merge(
    clean_df,
    on=["user_id", "company"],
    suffixes=("_neg", "_clean")
)

# 3. Compute delta from clean
delta_df_neg["delta_from_clean"] = (
    delta_df_neg["user_estimate_neg"] - delta_df_neg["user_estimate_clean"]
)

# 4. Filter users with more than 1 observation
user_counts = delta_df_neg["user_id"].value_counts()
valid_users = user_counts[user_counts > 1].index
delta_df_neg = delta_df_neg[delta_df_neg["user_id"].isin(valid_users)]

# 5. Fit mixed model if variance is sufficient
if delta_df_neg["delta_from_clean"].var() < 1e-5:
    print("Not enough variance in delta_from_clean to fit the model.")
else:
    try:
        model_neg = smf.mixedlm(
            "delta_from_clean ~ 1", 
            data=delta_df_neg, 
            groups=delta_df_neg["user_id"]
        )
        mixed_result_neg = model_neg.fit(reml=False, method="lbfgs")
        print(mixed_result_neg.summary())

        # Optional: random effects table
        random_df_neg = pd.DataFrame.from_dict(
            mixed_result_neg.random_effects, orient='index'
        )
        random_df_neg.columns = ["user_intercept"]
        print(random_df_neg)

    except Exception as e:
        print("Model fitting failed:", e)

# Tallennetaan kaikki kertoimet dictiin
coef_dict = {}

for user in df['user_id'].unique():
    user_df = df[df['user_id'] == user]
    model = ols("answer_delta ~ C(manipulation)", data=user_df).fit()
    coef_dict[user] = model.params

# Yhdistetään DataFrameksi
coef_df = pd.DataFrame(coef_dict).T  # transponoi: rivit käyttäjiä, sarakkeet kertoimia

# Näytetään kertoimien keskiarvot (populaatiomalli)
pop_model = coef_df.mean().to_frame(name='Mean_Coefficient')
pop_model

# Mixed model with fixed effects for manipulation, and random intercepts per user
model_intercept = smf.mixedlm(
    "user_estimate ~ C(manipulation)",  # Fixed effects for manipulation type
    data=df,
    groups=df["user_id"],               # Random intercept per user
    re_formula="1"                      # <- Only random intercept
)

# Fit the model
result_intercept = model_intercept.fit(reml=False, method="lbfgs")

# Show the summary
print(result_intercept.summary())

modeltest = smf.mixedlm(
    "user_estimate ~ C(manipulation)",         # Fixed effects: estimate based on manipulation type
    data=df,                            
    groups=df["user_id"],                       # Random intercepts: each user has their own baseline
    re_formula="~C(manipulation)"              # Random slopes: each user may react differently to manipulation
)

resulttest = modeltest.fit(reml=False, method="lbfgs")
print(resulttest.summary())

Malli ei näe muista ryhmiä ollenkaan ennustetaan vain yhtä manipulaatiota kerrallaan.

Random effectseistä taulukko.

Seuraava step mahdollisesti: Positive ja negative yhdessä. Saadaanko raportointi ilman referenssicasea.

Seuraavat analyysipolut positive vs. clean, negative vs. clean. Plottaa nämä läpi per käyttäjä ja per kuva. Sama mahdollisesti per koehenkilö

Verrataan eroa midlineen per kuva. Käyttäjäkohtaisesti ensisijaisesti per käyttäjä per kh.

  • Ensin keskiarvoistaa per käyttäjä, sitten tsekkaa mitä seuraavaksi.

Kuvaajakohtaisesti mahdollisesti? Onko kuvilla merkitystä - tämä voi olla esim. sanity check.

Regressiossa kysymys miten käyttäjät huomioidaan. Nykyään tehedään monitasomalli, jossa jokaisella koehenkilöllä on oma efektinsä ja tämän lisäksi ovat tietystä populaatiosta osa, jolla efekti. Eli oma + ryhmän vaikutus.

Monitasomalli: Layer 1 Sovitat mallin jokaiselle koehenkilölle erikseen Kaikista kertoimista keskiarvo, joka on populaatiomalli (fixed effect).
